The keenly awaited Medical Schemes Amendment Bill will not be published for comment until the Cabinet has approved the National Health Insurance Bill, Health Minister Aaron Motsoaledi says. The minister said after his budget speech earlier this month that the Medical Schemes Amendment Bill aimed to protect consumers, and would introduce a uniform tariff and scrap co-payments for a defined basket of benefits. Healthcare providers are anxiously waiting to see the details of this proposal, with doctor groups warning that a cap on their fees could prompt an exodus from the profession. The Cabinet announced on May 24 that it had approved the Medical Schemes Amendment Bill, fuelling speculation that it could be published in the Government Gazette within a matter of days. However, in an interview with Business Day on Monday evening, Motsoaledi said the two bills were "twinned" and would be published in the gazette together, once the Cabinet had approved the NHI Bill. The earliest it could do so would be at its next meeting on Wednesday, June 6, he said. Motsoaledi was not at last weekâ€™s Cabinet meeting, as he was attending a meeting of the World Health Assembly in Geneva.